t. By situating both countries in the Cold War, Conrad shows that the focus on the nation can be understood only within a transnational context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszGermany. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aHistoriographyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aHistoriographyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszGermany. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican occupation.  aasia.  acold war.  adefeat.  aengaging.  aeurope.  afascism.  agerman scholars.  agermany.  aglobal politics.  ahistorical perspective.  ahistorical.  ahistoriography.  ajapan.  ajapanese scholars.  alost nation.  amodern history.  anational past.  anonfiction.  aovercoming dark past.  aovercoming defeat.  apostwar germany.  apostwar japan.  areclamation.  areconstruction.  arevised history.  arevisionist history.  asocial history.  asurrender.  atransnational context.  aworld war ii.  aworld wars.  awwii.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025944740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094581440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945814/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY